# Data science and measurement principles

These rules ensure measurement is purposeful, statistically valid, privacy-respecting, and actionable. They apply whenever an AI agent implements analytics, reporting, dashboards, or data-driven features.

## Measure outcomes, not outputs

- **Lagging indicators** measure results (revenue, retention, task completion rate). They confirm whether you succeeded.
- **Leading indicators** predict lagging indicators (daily active users, activation rate, feature adoption). They tell you early whether you are on track.
- Before implementing any metric: identify which lagging indicator it predicts and how. If you cannot draw that connection, the metric is vanity.
- Common vanity metrics to avoid as primary measures: page views (without context), registered users (vs active), social follows.

## Event tracking design

- Name events using `noun_verb` convention: `button_clicked`, `form_submitted`, `session_started`, `payment_failed`.
- Track **decisions and outcomes**, not raw interactions. `checkout_completed` is more valuable than `button_clicked`.
- Every event must answer: Who did it? What was the context? What was the result?
- Standard event properties: `user_id` (anonymised), `session_id`, `timestamp`, `platform`, `event_name`, `properties: {}`.
- Never include personally identifiable information in event properties. User identifiers must be pseudonymous.
- Document every event in a tracking plan before implementing. Undocumented events become technical debt.

## Core Web Vitals (performance contract)

These are the minimum performance targets before shipping any web UI. Measure with Lighthouse and real-user monitoring (RUM).

| Metric | Good | Needs improvement | Poor |
|--------|------|-------------------|------|
| Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) | ≤2.5s | 2.5–4s | >4s |
| Interaction to Next Paint (INP) | ≤200ms | 200–500ms | >500ms |
| Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS) | ≤0.1 | 0.1–0.25 | >0.25 |

- LCP: optimise the largest above-the-fold element. Prioritise image loading with `fetchpriority="high"`.
- INP: avoid long tasks on the main thread. Defer non-critical JavaScript.
- CLS: set explicit `width` and `height` on all images and media. Reserve space for async content.

Measure Core Web Vitals in CI using Lighthouse CI. Do not ship if any metric moves from Good to Needs Improvement without a documented justification.

## Statistical validity

- **Minimum sample size**: calculate before starting any test. Use a power analysis (power ≥ 0.8, α ≤ 0.05). Tools: [statsig.com/sample-size-calculator](https://statsig.com/sample-size-calculator).
- **Do not stop a test early** because results look promising. Early stopping inflates false-positive rates.
- **One variable at a time**: A/B tests change one element. Multi-variate tests require exponentially larger samples to reach significance.
- **Two-week minimum runtime**: catch day-of-week effects that would otherwise skew results.
- **Practical significance ≠ statistical significance**: a 0.1% improvement may be statistically significant with a large enough sample but not worth shipping. Define minimum detectable effect before starting.
- p < 0.05 means there is a 5% chance your result is a false positive. Report confidence intervals alongside p-values.

## Data visualisation

Choose the chart type based on the question, not preference:

| Question | Chart type |
|---|---|
| How does X compare to Y? | Bar chart (horizontal for long labels) |
| How does X change over time? | Line chart |
| What is the composition of X? | Stacked bar or treemap (not pie for >3 segments) |
| Is there a relationship between X and Y? | Scatter plot |
| How is X distributed? | Histogram or box plot |

**Formatting rules:**
- Start y-axis at zero for bar charts. Never truncate to exaggerate differences.
- Label axes with units. A number without a unit is ambiguous.
- Remove chart junk: no 3D effects, no unnecessary gridlines, no decorative elements.
- Use colour to encode a variable, not to decorate. A single-colour bar chart is clearer than a rainbow.
- Provide a text summary of key insight alongside every chart — do not make users interpret alone.

## Privacy-first analytics (POPIA / GDPR alignment)

- **Collect minimum necessary data.** If you are not sure you will use a property, do not collect it.
- Anonymise user identifiers at the point of collection. Never store raw emails or names in analytics events.
- Implement a **data retention policy** before going to production. Default: delete raw event data after 90 days; keep aggregated metrics.
- All analytics collection must be disclosed in the privacy policy. Do not add a new tracking tool without updating documentation.
- Respect `Do Not Track` headers and cookie consent. Provide a genuine opt-out that works.
- Do not send analytics data cross-border without understanding the legal basis (POPIA requires adequate protection).
- PII categories to never include in events: full name, email, ID number, phone number, location (beyond country/region), health data, financial data.

## Dashboard design principles

- **One primary metric per view.** A dashboard with 50 metrics communicates nothing. The most important number should be visually dominant.
- Always show **context alongside the number**: comparison to previous period, target, or benchmark. A metric without context cannot drive a decision.
- Design for the decision, not the data. Before building a dashboard, ask: what decision will this dashboard enable?
- Colour in dashboards is semantic: green = good, yellow = attention, red = action required. Use consistently.
- Refresh intervals must be appropriate to the metric. Real-time updates for operational metrics; daily aggregates for strategic metrics.

## A/B testing checklist

Before starting any A/B test:
- [ ] Define the hypothesis: "We believe that [change] will cause [outcome] because [reason]."
- [ ] Calculate minimum sample size
- [ ] Define primary metric and guardrail metrics (metrics that must not degrade)
- [ ] Set test duration (minimum 2 weeks)
- [ ] Confirm random assignment is working correctly
- [ ] Define what "winner" means before seeing results

After the test:
- [ ] Report confidence intervals, not just p-value
- [ ] Check guardrail metrics
- [ ] Document the result regardless of outcome — negative results have value

## Hard stops

- Do not collect PII in analytics events.
- Do not ship a dashboard without a text interpretation of the key insight.
- Do not start a y-axis at a non-zero value in a bar chart.
- Do not draw conclusions from fewer than the calculated minimum sample size.
- Do not implement analytics tracking without a corresponding tracking plan entry.
